Glasswork, real name Nadia Vasquez, is a 31-year-old construction site manager who was driving one of the two cars involved in the Crash. She had just finished a night shift and was driving home. She was not part of any heroic or villainous world before or after the Crash, and she would like very much to return to not being part of it.

The Quantum Spin Liquid gave her the ability to transmute any solid material into glass and back, at will. She can shape the glass as it forms — smooth it into barriers, draw it into filaments, fracture it into shards that move at her direction. On a good day it is genuinely beautiful. On a bad day she has no control over it at all.

The side effect is emotional: strong feelings — fear, grief, anger, even sudden joy — trigger her powers involuntarily. Every window in her apartment has been replaced multiple times. She stopped having people over. She once lost control during a phone call about her mother and shattered every piece of glass in a diner. She paid for it. She does not eat at diners anymore.

She is in therapy, independently, at a different practice from the Meridian Center. She is not affiliated with Therapy or the Justice Alliance and has declined approaches from both. She doesn't want a team. She wants to go back to work, but the involuntary transformations make construction sites dangerous, and the union rep's face when she tried to explain it was something she would like to stop seeing when she closes her eyes.

She uses the name Glasswork only informally — a coworker called her that when her powers first manifested, half-joking, and it stuck the way nicknames do when they're accurate.

She spends time at the Crash Site, trying to understand what happened to her. This is how she met Threshold. They don't talk much when they're there. They don't need to. It helps, a little, to not be the only person standing on that stretch of highway looking at a place that changed everything and got no answers back.

She is undeclared. She is not choosing a side. She is trying to get through the week.
